Part 2: Experimental Setup¶

The goal of the next few sections is to design an experiment to predict the median home value for an instance in the data.

2.1 Begin by writing a function to compute the Root Mean Squared Error for a list of numbers¶

You can find the sqrt function in the Numpy package. Furthermore the details of RMSE can be found on Wikipedia

In [348]:
"""
Function
--------
compute_rmse

Given two arrays, one of actual values and one of predicted values,
compute the Roote Mean Squared Error

Parameters
----------
predictions : array
    Array of numerical values corresponding to predictions for each of the N observations

yvalues : array
    Array of numerical values corresponding to the actual values for each of the N observations

Returns
-------
rmse : int
    Root Mean Squared Error of the prediction

Example
-------
>>> print compute_rmse((2,2,3),(0,2,6)
2.16
"""
def compute_rmse(predictions, yvalues):
    rmse = math.sqrt((sum((predictions - yvalues)**2))/len(yvalues))
    return rmse

y_hat = np.array([2,2,3])
y = np.array([0,2,6])
compute_rmse(y_hat,y)
Out[348]:
2.0816659994661326

Part 3: Nearest Neighbors¶

3.1 Nearest Neighbors: Distance function¶

Let's try and build a machine learning algorithm to beat the "Average Value" baseline that you computed above. Soon you will implement the Nearest Neighbor algorithm, but first you need to create a distance metric to measure the distance (and similarity) between two instances. Write a generic function to compute the L-Norm distance (called the p-norm distance on Wikipedia). Verify that your function works by computing the Euclidean distance between the points (3,4) and (6,8).

In [353]:
"""
Function
--------
distance

Given two instances and a value for L, return the L-Norm distance between them

Parameters
----------
x1, x2 : array
    Array of numerical values corresponding to predictions for each of the N observations

L: int
    Value of L to use in computing distances

Returns
-------
dist : int
    The L-norm distance between instances

Example
-------
>>> print distance((3,4),(6,8),2)
7

"""
# distance function for arrays
def distance(x1, x2, L): # where x1 is array of instances (any size) and x2 is query data
    dist = (np.sum(abs(x1-x2)**L, axis=1))**(1/L)
    return dist

print(distance(np.array([[3,4]]),np.array([[6,8]]), 2))

[5.]

3.2 Basic Nearest Neighbor algorithm¶

Now things get fun. Your task is to implement a basic nearest neighbor algorithm from scratch. Your simple model will use two input features (CRIM and RM) and a single output (MEDV). In other words, you are modelling the relationship between median home value and crime rates and house size.

Use your training data (bdata_train) to "fit" your model, although as you know, with Nearest Neighbors there is no real training, you just need to keep your training data in memory. Write a function that predicts, for each instance in the testing data (bdata_test), the median home value using the nearest neighbor algorithm we discussed in class. Since this is a small dataset, you can simply compare your test instance to every instance in the training set, and return the MEDV value of the closest training instance. Have your function take L as an input, where L is passed to the distance function.

Compute the RMSE for the Nearest Neighbor predictions on the test set, using the Euclidean distance. Report an estimate of the total time taken by your code to predict the nearest neighbors for all the values in the test data set.

In [354]:
"""
Function
--------
nneighbor

Given an instance, finds target value of nearest neighbor in the training feature space.

Parameters
---------
train : array
    Selected features in training data with target feature as the last column
    
test : array
    Selected features in test data with target feature as the last column
    
L : int
    Value of L to use in computing distances

Returns
-------
rmse : int
    Root Mean Squared Error of the prediction

Example
-------
>>> nneighbor(np.array([[1,4,5],[9,8,5]]), np.array([[8,4,3],[1,7,8]]), 2)
array([5., 5.])
"""
from operator import itemgetter
import time

def nneighbor(train, test, L): 
    start_time = time.time()
    yhat = np.zeros(len(test)) # empty array to hold predicted values for test instances
    for j in range(0,len(test)): 
        distances = np.zeros((len(train), 2)) # empty array to hold distances 
        dist = distance(train[:,0:len(train[1])-1], test[j,0:len(test[1])-1], L) # find distances between test point j and all training points
        distances[:,0], distances[:,1] = dist, train[:,-1] # add distances and target value to array
        distances = distances[distances[:,0].argsort()] # sort by shortest distance
        yhat[j] = distances[0,1] # add target value of nearest neighbor to yhat
    print("Time taken: " + str(round(time.time() - start_time,2)) + " seconds")
    return yhat # return predicted target values

# get two columns of interest into array where each row is an instance
x1 = np.array([bdat_train['CRIM'], bdat_train['RM'], bdat_train['MEDV']]).T # training data
x2 = np.array([bdat_test['CRIM'], bdat_test['RM'], bdat_test['MEDV']]).T # test data

# run it!
preds1 = nneighbor(x1,x2,2) # why are there so many columns???

# compute RMSE
compute_rmse(preds1, x2[:,len(x2[1])-1])

3.3 Results and Normalization¶

If you were being astute, you would have noticed that we never normalized our features -- a big no-no with Nearest Neighbor algorithms. Write a generic normalization function that takes as input an array of values for a given feature, and returns the normalized array (subtract the mean and divide by the standard deviation).

Re-run the Nearest Neighbor algorithm on the normalized dataset (still just using CRIM and RM as input), and compare the RMSE from this method with your previous RMSE evaluations.

NOTE: To normalize properly, best practice is to compute the mean and standard deviation on the training set, and use these values to normalize the testing dataset. However, for this problem set, it is okay if you separately normalize each dataset using the respective mean and standard deviation.

In [356]:
"""
Function
--------
normalize

Normalizes each feature of a dataset by subtracting mean of feature and dividing by standard deviation of feature

Parameters
---------
raw_data : DataFrame
    Selected features with target feature as the last column

Returns
-------
normalized_data : DataFrame
    Normalized data

Example
-------
>>> p=pd.DataFrame({'one' : [1., 2., 3., 4.],
                'two' : [4., 3., 2., 1.]})
>>> normalize(p)
"""
def normalize(raw_data):
    feats = len(raw_data.columns)-1 # last column of raw_data is target feature
    normalized_data = raw_data.copy() # set normalized data equal to raw input data
    colmeans = raw_data.iloc[:,0:feats].mean(axis=0) # get means of each feature except target 
    colsds = raw_data.iloc[:,0:feats].std(axis=0) # get SD of each feature except target
    normalized_data.iloc[:,0:feats] = (raw_data.iloc[:,0:feats] - colmeans) / colsds # normalize features except target
    return normalized_data

bdat_train_norm = normalize(bdat_train) # normalize training data separately
bdat_test_norm = normalize(bdat_test) # normalize testing data separately

x1_norm = np.array([bdat_train_norm['CRIM'], bdat_train_norm['RM'], bdat_train_norm['MEDV']]).T # create array of selected training features
x2_norm = np.array([bdat_test_norm['CRIM'], bdat_test_norm['RM'], bdat_test_norm['MEDV']]).T # create array of selected testing features

preds2 = nneighbor(x1_norm, x2_norm, 2) # run nneighbors with normalized data

compute_rmse(preds2, x2_norm[:,len(x2[1])-1]) # compute RMSE

Time taken: 0.02 seconds

The normalized data actually does marginally worse (RMSE + ~0.2) than the non-normalized data. This is not unexpected -- normalizing the data simply prevents any one feature from having an outsized weight on the distance calculation, it doesn't necessarily reduce the RMSE.

3.5 Cross-Validation¶

The more you tinkered with your features and distance function, the higher the risk that you overfit your training data. To prevent this sort of overfitting, you need to use cross-validation (see K-fold cross-validation). Here you must implement a simple k-fold cross-validation algorithm yourself. The function you write here will be used several more times in this problem set, so do your best to write efficient code! (Note that the sklearn package has a built-in K-fold iterator -- you should not be invoking that or any related algorithms in this section of the problem set.)

Use 10-fold cross-validation and report the average RMSE for Nearest Neighbors using Euclidean distance with CRIM and RM input features, as well as the total running time for the full run of 10 folds. In other words, randomly divide your dataset into 10 equally-sized samples, and for each of 10 iterations (the "folds"), use 9 samples as "training data" (even though there is no training in k-NN!), and the remaining 1 sample for testing. Compute the RMSE of that particular test set, then move on to the next iteration. Report the average RMSE across the 10 iterations.

In [362]:
"""
Function
--------
kfold_crossval

Given a dataset and number of folds, k, returns indices in dataset corresponding to test and training instances for k number of iterations

Parameters
----------
data : array
    Array of data

k : integer
    Number of folds in cross validation
    
Returns
-------
kfolds : list
    List of k-lists with indices of the dataset rows contained in each fold. 
    Can index the dataset to return train/test split for every fold. 
"""
import random
from random import randrange

def kfold_crossval(data, k):
    fold_size = int(len(data)/k) # find how big folds must be for k-number of folds
    rows = list(range(len(data))) # a list of indices for each row in the dataset from which we will randomly pick folds
    data_split = [] # holds indices of folds ("test" data)
    for i in range(k): 
        fold = [] # holds four fold indices
        while len(fold) < fold_size: 
            ind = randrange(len(rows)) # randomly pulls one row 
            fold.append(rows.pop(ind)) # appends the row and also removes it from the list of rows so it can't be pulled again
        data_split.append(fold) # adds the list of four fold indices to list of lists
    return data_split

#================ Get k-folds
x1 = np.array([bdat_train_norm['CRIM'], bdat_train_norm['RM'], bdat_train_norm['MEDV']]).T # create array of training data
kfolds = kfold_crossval(x1, 10) # run it! get folds

#================ Use k-folds to iterate through nearest neighbors model
rmse = [] # list for RMSEs
rows = list(range(len(x1))) # list of dataset indices
for i in range(len(kfolds)):
    train = x1[[x for x in rows if x not in kfolds[i]], :2] # train data = slice of dataset corresponding to NOT k-folds
    test = x1[kfolds[i], :2] # test data = slice of dataset corresponding to k-folds
    preds = nneighbor(train, test, 2) # run nearest neighbors
    rmse.append(compute_rmse(preds, test[:,len(test[1])-1])) # get RMSE
    
sum(rmse)/len(rmse) # mean of RMSEs

3.6 K-Nearest Neighbors Algorithm¶

Implement the K-Nearest Neighbors algorithm. Using 10-fold cross validation, report the RMSE for K=3 and the running time of the algorithm.

In [371]:
"""
Function
--------
knn

Given a dataset and number of folds, k, returns indices in dataset corresponding to test and training instances for k number of iterations

Parameters
----------
train : array
    Array of data

k : integer
    Number of folds in cross validation
    
Returns
-------
yhat : array
    Predicted target values of test data
"""
def knn(train, test, L, K): 
    start_time = time.time()
    yhat = np.zeros(len(test)) # empty array to hold predicted values for test instances
    for j in range(0,len(test)): 
        distances = np.zeros((len(train), 2)) # empty array to hold distances 
        dist = distance(train[:,0:len(train[1])-1], test[j,0:len(test[1])-1], L) # find distances between test point j and all training points
        distances[:,0], distances[:,1] = dist, train[:,-1] # add distances and target value to array
        distances = distances[distances[:,0].argsort()] # sort by shortest distance
        yhat[j] = np.mean(distances[K-1,1]) # add mean target value of k-nearest neighbors to yhat
    print("Time taken: " + str(round(time.time() - start_time, 2)) + " seconds")
    return yhat # return predicted target values

x1 = np.array([bdat_train_norm['CRIM'], bdat_train_norm['RM'], bdat_train_norm['MEDV']]).T # training data
x2 = np.array([bdat_test_norm['CRIM'], bdat_test_norm['RM'], bdat_test_norm['MEDV']]).T # test data

preds = knn(x1, x2, 2, 3) # get target value predictions for K=3
compute_rmse(preds, x2[:,len(x2[1])-1]) # compute RMSE
